outcomes.title: Correlation and Regression
outcomes.description: I can use correlation and regression to describe relationships between two variables in a set of data.
outcomes.template:
The Scenario:

In 2019, a group of researchers collected the data from a sample of 222 car models and looked at the impact of different characteristics of the cars on the MSRP (manufacturers’ suggested retail price). They ran a regression analysis. The scatterplots and regression lines are shown below for MSRP vs HP (horsepower) and MSRP vs Engine size (in liters).

Below is the information about the regression model for the scatter plot above.

Equation and R^2 value for the manufacturers' suggested retail price (MSRP) vs horsepower (HP).

MSRP = -3162.10 + 168.64 * HP

The R^2 value for this regression model is 0.582

Below is the information about the regression model for the scatter plot above.

Equation and R^2 value for the manufacturers' suggested retail price (MSRP) vs engine size (in liters)

MSRP = 18017.87 + 7976.67 * Engine size

The R^2 value for this regression model is 0.193

Use the two scatter plots and the given information about the regression models to answer the questions below.

Which model, if any, would you use to predict the price of a car? Explain why your choice would be the best model to get an accurate prediction.

MSRP vs HP is the better model to make predictions with because it has a higher R^2 value

What do you predict the MSRP of a vehicle with {{HP}} HP to be? Explain why you used the model you did and show all work. Put your final answer into a complete sentence to answer the question.

${{answer_2}}

Would you use one of the regression models to predict the MSRP of a vehicle with an engine size of 3.2 liters? Why or why not?

No, the model has a weak correlation.

There is a dot at ({{point_4x}}, {{point_4y}}) on the MSRP vs horsepower graph. Explain what this dot represents in context of the study

A specific car in the dataset with {{point_4x}} horsepower and a MSRP of ${{point_4y}}

Compute the correlation coefficient, R, for the MSRP vs horsepower model. Explain the meaning of R in the context of the scenario.

.7629, there is a strong positive relationship between horsepower and MSRP so as the horsepower goes up, on average so does the MSRP.

The Scenario:

A researcher is interested in examining the relationships between various characteristics of the human body. She measured 22 subjects to see what measurements were most strongly correlated. In this study, mass is measured in kilograms (kg) and all other measurements are in centimeters (cm).

Below are two scatterplots. The first shows the correlation between mass and chest size. The second shows the correlation between mass and head size.

Below is the information about the regression model for the scatter plot above.

Equation and R^2 value for body mass (kg) vs chest size (cm).

Mass = -51.96 + 1.263 * (chest size)

The R^2 value for this regression is .602

Below is the information about the regression model for the scatter plot above.

Equation and R^2 value for body mass (kg) vs chest size (cm).

Mass = -51.06 + 2.153 * (head size)

The R^2 value for this regression is .061

Use the two scatter plots and the given information about the regression models to answer the questions below.

Which model, if any, would you use to predict the mass of someone? Explain why your choice would be the best model to get an accurate prediction

body mass vs. chest size is the better model to make predictions with because it has a higher R^2 value

What do you predict the mass of someone with a chest size of {{chest_2}}? Explain why you used the model you did and show all work. Put your final answer into a complete sentence to answer the question.

{{answer_2}} kg

Would you use one of the regression models to predict the mass of someone with a {{size_3}} cm chest? Why or why not?

No, outside of the data range or extrapolation

There is a dot at ({{point_x}}, {{point_y}}) on the mass vs {{ind_var4}} size graph. Explain what this dot represents in context of the study.

The dot represents a specific person in the study that has a mass of {{point_y}} kg and {{ind_var4}} size of {{point_x}} cm.

Compute the correlation coefficient, R, for the mass vs. chest model. Explain the meaning of R in the context of the problem.

.78 and as the chest size goes up, on average so does the mass of a person.

The Scenario:

Every year several different variables are collected from each state. Three of those variables are SAT scores, proportion of students taking the SAT and population of the state.

Below are two scatterplots, one showing the relationship between average SAT Verbal scores and proportion of students taking the SAT. The other is showing the relationship between average SAT Verbal scores and state population.

Below is the information about the regression model for the scatter plot above.

Equation and R^2 value for average SAT Verbal scores vs proportion of students taking the SAT.

SAT Verbal Score = 575.6 - 101.3 * (proportion taking SAT)

The R^2 value for this regression is .790

Below is the information about the regression model for the scatter plot above.

Equation and R^2 value for average SAT Verbal scores vs state population.

SAT Verbal Score = 543.7 - .000001446 * (population)

The R^2 value for this regression is .077

Use the two scatter plots and the given information about the regression models to answer the questions below.

Which model, if any, would you use to predict the State's average SAT verbal score? Explain why your choice would be the best model to get an accurate prediction.

SAT verbal score vs proportion of testers is the better model to make predictions with because it has a higher R^2 value

What do you predict the average SAT verbal score to be if the proportion of testers were {{number_2}}? Explain why you used the model you did and show all work. Put your final answer into a complete sentence to answer the question.

{{answer_2}}

Would you use one of the regression models to predict the average 2004 SAT verbal score of a state whose population is {{pop_3}}? Why or why not?

No, low correlation

There is a dot at ({{point_x}}, {{point_y}}) on the SAT verbal score vs the {{ind_var4}} graph. Explain what this dot represents in context of the study.

The dot represents a specific state that in 2004, {{point_y}} was the average SAT verbal score for the state and {{point_x}} was the {{ind_var4}}.

Compute the correlation coefficient, R, for the SAT Verbal scores vs proportion of students taking the SAT model. Explain the meaning of R in the context of the problem.

-0.89, as the proportion of tester in a state goes up on average the state's average SAT verbal score goes down.

The Scenario:

Let's talk about movies. What is your favorite movie and how much money did it make? Here is data about how much 5,222 different movies made and how much they cost in millions of dollars .

Below are two scatterplots, one showing the relationship between worldwide gross revenues and budget. The other is showing the relationship between worldwide gross revenues and domestic gross revenues.

Below is the information about the regression model for the scatter plot above.

Equation and R^2 value for worldwide gross revenues vs budget.

Worldwide Gross Revenue = -7.117 + 3.119 * (Budget)

The R^2 value for this regression is 0.558

Below is the information about the regression model for the scatter plot above.

Equation and R^2 value for worldwide gross revenues vs domestic gross revenues.

Worldwide Gross Revenue = -9.62 + 2.3922 * (Domestic Gross Revenues)

The R^2 value for this regression is .877

Use the two scatter plots and the given information about the regression models to answer the questions below.

Which model, if any, would you use to predict the worldwide gross revenue of a movie? Explain why your choice would be the best model to get an accurate prediction.

Either model can be used but the Worldwide gross revenue vs domestic gross is the better model to make predictions with because it has a higher R^2 value

What do you predict the worldwide gross revenue of a movie with a domestic gross revenue of {{money_2}} million dollars? Explain why you used the model you did and show all work. Put your final answer into a complete sentence to answer the question.

{{answer_2}} million dollars

Would you use one of the regression models to predict the worldwide gross revenue of a movie with domestic gross revenue of ${{money_3}} million? Why or why not?

No, outside of the data range or extrapolation

There is a dot at ({{point_x}}, {{point_y}}) on the Worldwide gross revenue vs it's {{ind_var4}} graph. Explain what this dot represents in context of the dataset.

The dot represents a specific movie in the dataset that made {{point_y}} million dollars in worldwide gross revenue and had {{ind_var4}} of {{point_x}} million dollars.

Compute the correlation coefficient, R, for the worldwide gross revenues vs budget model. Explain the meaning of R in the context of the problem

0.75, as the movie's budget goes up on average so does it's worldwide gross revenue
